Inheritance

This lesson explains and demonstrates how inheritance works with POM files.

We learned about Super POM and how all POMs extend from this base POM. Maven allows us to set any POM as the parent POM for a project. Introducing a parent POM can help extract out common configurations among an organization’s projects and consolidate them in a parent POM from which all other projects inherit. This avoids unnecessary repetition and verbosity. For example, a company can decide to have a parent POM that lists the organization’s internal Maven repositories thus allowing sub-teams to simply extend from the parent POM and not worry about the location of repositories. POM inheritance allows the following to be merged:

  • dependencies
  • developers and contributors
  • plugin lists (including reports)
  • plugin executions with matching ids
  • plugin configuration
  • resources

In essence, POM files at the bottom of the hierarchy declare that they inherit from a specific parent POM higher up in the hierarchy. The parent POM can then be used to share certain properties and details of configuration

Let’s dive into an example and see inheritance at work. We’ll work with Project3 with the directory structure shown as follows:

In the above example we work with Project3. The root directory of the project consists of a POM file with the following contents:

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<project>
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>io.datajek</groupId>
    <artifactId>project3</artifactId>
    <version>1</version>

    <packaging>pom</packaging>
    <name>ParentProject</name>

</project>

Note how we have changed the <packaging> value to pom from the default value jar. The /Project3 directory has a subdirectory called Child, which in turn contains another POM file with the following contents:

<project>
    <parent>
        <groupId>io.datajek</groupId>
        <artifactId>parent-project</artifactId>
        <version>1</version>
    </parent>

    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>io.datajek</groupId>
    <artifactId>project3a</artifactId>
    <version>1</version>


    <packaging>jar</packaging>
    <name>ChildProject</name>

</project>

Notice the section under the <parent> element. We designate the POM file of the parent project as the parent POM for the child project. So how do we see inheritance in action? We can add the following <developer> snippet in the parent project’s POM file and then compute the effective POM for the child project. If inheritance works correctly we should see the <developer> snippet appear in the effective POM for the child project.

    <developers>
        <developer>
            <name>DataJek</name>
        </developer>
    </developers>

Running mvn help:effective-pom -Dverbose should result in the following:

The output also shows which parent project the <developers> tag’s content are being inherited from.

The astute reader would observe that, in this setup, we have nested the child project under the parent project which may not always be feasible. We could also have a setup where the child and parent directories are siblings and at the same level. Consider a project that has the following directory structure:

There are two ways to build the child project in such a setup:

  1. We can first build the parent project which will install the parent project’s POM in the local repository, ~/.m2, and then build the child project. If we build the parent project first, we’ll see the following message:
[INFO] Installing /Project4/Parent/pom.xml to /root/.m2/repository/io/datajek/project4/1/project4-1.pom

When the child project is built it can download the parent project’s POM from the local repository.

  1. The second method we can use is applying a relative path to the location of the parent POM file. The child project’s POM file will change as follows:
    <parent>
        <groupId>io.datajek</groupId>
        <artifactId>parent4</artifactId>
        <version>1</version>
        <relativePath>../Parent/pom.xml</relativePath>
    </parent>

# Change directory to Project4
cd /Project4
# Change directory to Child
cd Child
# Run mvn install and verify that you see an error. The Child POM
# can't access the Parent's POM
mvn install
# Now Change directory to Parent project
cd ../Parent
# Run mvn install and verify the Parent's POM file is installed in the
# ~/.m2 directory
mvn install
# Change directory back to Child and run mvn install. Now the Child
# project builds correctly.
cd ../Child
mvn install
# Now we'll delete the Parent POM installed in the ~/.m2 repository and
# change the Child POM's file with a relative path to the parent POM.
rm -rf /root/.m2/repository/io/datajek/project4
# Add the followin snippet to the Child's POM's parent section
#
#     <relativePath>../Parent/pom.xml</relativePath>
#
###############################################################
